\(\sin 59^\circ = \cos k^\circ \Rightarrow \cos(90^\circ - 59^\circ) = \cos k^\circ \Rightarrow \cos 31^\circ = \cos k^\circ\).

Thus \(k = 31^\circ + 360^\circ n\) or \(k = -31^\circ + 360^\circ n\). For \(270^\circ < k < 360^\circ\), take \(n=1\): \(k = -31^\circ + 360^\circ = 329^\circ\).

\boxed{329}

Complete squares: 4(x-1)² - (y-1)² = 4 → center (1,1).  
90° clockwise: (x,y)→(y,-x) → new center (1,-1).  
\boxed{(1,-1)}

\(x^2 - 5x - 7 = x \Rightarrow x^2 - 6x - 7 = 0\).  
Roots: \(7, -1\). Sum: \(6\).  

\boxed{6}

For an \(n\)-sided convex polygon, diagonals = \(\binom{n}{2} - n\).  
For \(n=100\): \(\binom{100}{2} = 4950\), minus 100 gives \(4850\).  
\boxed{4850}

For circles with radii 8 and 12, centers 24 apart, internal tangent length \(L\) satisfies \(L^2 + (8+12)^2 = 24^2\).  
So \(L^2 = 576 - 400 = 176\), thus \(L = \sqrt{176} = 4\sqrt{11}\).  
\boxed{4\sqrt{11}}
